'''Barkatullah''' (also spelt as '''Barakatullah''' or '''Barkat Ullah''') was a [[Christian]] [[Christian apologist|apologist]] and a [[Converts from Islam|convert from Islam]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=Wxu1yn8VbiEC&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=Allama+Barkat+Ullah&source=bl&ots=tvu0P1Be8H&sig=jzjMJe-hXIAmEPLuBG6Xh3NcBEs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBtYi92qDYAhWMqI8KHbKRBl0Q6AEIYDAO#v=onepage&q=Allama%2520Barkat%2520Ullah&f=false |title=Understanding Asian Mission Movements |last=Tan |first=Kang San |last2=Ingleby |first2=Jonathan |last3=Cozens |first3=Simon |date=2011 |publisher=Wide Margin |isbn=9780956594389 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cuwap.org/node/5 |title=Barkat-Ullah (d. 1960) |website=www.cuwap.org |language=en |access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=JijYCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA601&lpg=PA601&dq=Archdeacon+Barkatullah+India&source=bl&ots=8fobryuqy9&sig=TaqleXBM5MEHX8EhFbsRMwqSdsQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjB4-Wb-qDYAhXjDMAKHRgVBrgQ6AEIQjAE#v=onepage&q=Archdeacon%2520Barkatullah%2520India&f=false |title=The Oxford Handbook of Anglican Studies |last=Chapman |first=Mark David |last2=Clarke |first2=Sathianathan |last3=Percy |first3=Martyn |date=2015-10-15 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199218561 |language=en}}</ref> He was [[Baptism|baptised]] at the age of 16 years on 7 July 1907.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=kF9EvgAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:%2522Barakat+1891-+Ullah%2522&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiam6W0-6DYAhWLwBQKHZi1C5oQ6AEIJjAA |title=FROM KARBALA TO CALVARY |last=Ullah |first=Barakat 1891- |date=2016-08-26 |publisher=WENTWORTH Press |isbn=9781362122227 |language=en}}</ref> He worked as a [[lecturer]] in [[Edwardes College|Edwardes College]], and [[Forman Christian College]] from 1914 until his [[ordination]] in 1923. He also served in the Henry Martyn School of Islamic Studies in [[Aligarh]] after his retirement in 1956. He has authored several [[Urdu]] volumes in his contribution to the [[Christian apologetics]]. He was also the member of the Royal Asiatic Society. He died in 1971.
