{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Rosaleen McDonagh | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = Rosaleen McDonagh | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Sligo]], [[Ireland]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Irish | education = Trinity College Dublin | alma_mater = | known_for = playwright, activist | notable_works = }}
'''Rosaleen McDonagh''' is an activist, playwright and Irish Traveller.
==Early life== McDonagh was born in [[Sligo]] and is the fourth of twenty children. She was born with a disability. She spent ten years working in the [[Pavee Point Traveller and Roma Centre]] in the Violence against women programme. McDonagh got a BA in Biblical and Theological Studies. She then went on to complete an MPhil in Ethnic and Racial Studies, and an MPhil in Creative Writing, all from [[Trinity College Dublin]]. She is a PhD candidate in [[Northumbria University]]. <ref name="aosdana">{{cite web |title=Rosaleen McDonagh - Current Member {{!}} Aosdana |url=http://aosdana.artscouncil.ie/Members/Literature/McDonagh.aspx |website=aosdana.artscouncil.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Interviews - Development & Alumni - Trinity College Dublin |url=https://www.tcd.ie/alumni/alumni/interviews/rosaleen-mcdonagh.php |website=www.tcd.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McDonagh |first1=Rosaleen |title=Column: The personal assistant is so important, but government u-turn is no comfort |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/readme/disability-protests-government-u-turn-589070-Sep2012/ |website=TheJournal.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McDonagh |first1=Rosaleen |title=Column: Bringing disabilities into the abortion debate is exploitative and confusing |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/readme/column-bringing-disabilities-into-the-abortion-debate-is-exploitative-and-confusing-1005172-Jul2013/ |website=TheJournal.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rosaleen Mcdonagh {{!}} The Irish Times |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/topics/topics-7.1213540?article=true&tag_person=Rosaleen+Mcdonagh |work=www.irishtimes.com |language=en}}</ref>
==Career== McDonagh has been an activist for the [[Irish Travellers]] community. She writes for [[The Irish Times]] as well as having written a number of plays focusing typically on the feminist Traveller perspective. One of her plays, ''Rings'', was performed at VAS in Washington in June 2010. Another was shortlisted for the PJ O’ Connor radio play Awards in 2010. [[Colum McCann]] chose her to adapt his novel ''Zoli'' for stage. McDonagh has had work commissioned by RTE. McDonagh has worked with theatre groups like Fishamble and Graeae Theatre. She had a play directed by the [[Olivier award]] winner, [[Jim Culleton]]. She is a member of [[Aosdána]], the first from the Traveller community.<ref name="aosdana"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Rosaleen McDonagh – First Traveller elected to Aosdána, Pavee Point |url=https://www.paveepoint.ie/rosaleen-mcdonagh-first-traveller-elected-to-aosdana/ |website=www.paveepoint.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Irish Playography |url=http://www.irishplayography.com/person.aspx?personid=42149 |website=www.irishplayography.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=She's Not Mine by Rosaleen McDonagh |url=https://www.rte.ie/drama/radio/plays/life/2012/0402/647029-genres-life-shesnotmine/ |website=RTE.ie}}</ref>
McDonagh was also the first Traveller to run for election to the [[Seanad]] standing in 2002 and 2007, although she was not successful.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rosaleen McDonagh {{!}} Irish Election Literature |url=https://irishelectionliterature.com/tag/rosaleen-mcdonagh/ |website=irishelectionliterature.com |language=en}}</ref>
